<paragraph blockId="2.[151,620,1745,1772]" box="[151,620,1745,1772]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,620,1745,1772]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Menzies, 1962" authorityName="Menzies" authorityYear="1962" box="[151,620,1745,1772]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,620,1745,1772]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,417,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Haploniscus rostratus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Menzies" box="[432,611,1745,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" refString="Menzies, R. J. (1962) The isopods of abyssal depths in the Atlantic Ocean. Vema Research Series, 1, 79 - 206." type="journal article" year="1962">
Menzies, 
<number box="[551,611,1745,1771]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="1962.0">1962</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1816,2021]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,680]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
The known distribution of 
<taxonomicName box="[458,593,1818,1841]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis box="[458,593,1818,1841]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">H. rostratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to abyssal depths of 
<quantity box="[978,1137,1816,1840]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.112" metricValueMax="5.647" metricValueMin="4.577" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" unit="m" value="5112.0" valueMax="5647.0" valueMin="4577.0">4577–5647 m</quantity>
, geographically extending from the southern part of the Cape Basin over the 
<collectingCountry box="[719,801,1853,1877]" name="Angola" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Angola</collectingCountry>
Basin to the 
<collectingCountry box="[951,1032,1853,1877]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Guinea</collectingCountry>
Basin. The 
<typeStatus box="[1169,1217,1854,1878]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">type</typeStatus>
locality of the species is in the Cape Basin. Using a morphological approach, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brokeland" box="[834,1046,1888,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" refString="Brokeland, W. (2010 a) Redescription of Haploniscus rostratus (Menzies, 1962) (Crustacea: Peracarida: Isopoda) with observations on the postmarsupial development, size ranges and distribution. Zootaxa, 2521, 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="a">
Brökeland (
<number box="[966,1025,1888,1912]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="2010.0">2010</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
studied specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[1300,1436,1890,1913]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis box="[1300,1436,1890,1913]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">H. rostratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected north and south of the Walvis Ridge. The role of the ridge as a potential barrier to gene flow and hence allopatric divergence or speciation has been discussed (
<bibRefCitation author="Brandt" box="[785,1001,1960,1985]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" refString="Brandt, A., Brenke, N., Andres, H., Brix, S., Guerrero-Kommritz, J., Muhlenhardt-Siegel, U. &amp; Wagele, J. (2005) Diversity of peracarid crustaceans (Malacostraca) from the abyssal plain of the Angola basin. Organisms Diversity &amp; Evolution, 5 (Supplement 1), 105 - 112." type="journal article" year="2005">
Brandt 
<emphasis box="[873,931,1961,1985]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[940,1001,1960,1984]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). For 
<taxonomicName authority="Brokeland" authorityName="Brokeland" authorityYear="2010" box="[1070,1436,1960,1985]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis box="[1070,1207,1962,1985]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">H. rostratus</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brokeland" box="[1223,1436,1960,1984]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" refString="Brokeland, W. (2010 a) Redescription of Haploniscus rostratus (Menzies, 1962) (Crustacea: Peracarida: Isopoda) with observations on the postmarsupial development, size ranges and distribution. Zootaxa, 2521, 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="a">
Brökeland (
<number box="[1357,1416,1960,1984]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="2010.0">2010</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
found no significant morphological differences across the Walvis Ridge and consequently stated that populations on either side do not represent allopatric sibling species but rather are members of a single species distributed across the ridge. However, since distinct species may be morphologically very similar or even indistinguishable (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Held" box="[209,454,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" refString="Held, C. &amp; Wagele, J. (2005) Cryptic speciation in the giant Antarctic isopod Glyptonotus antarcticus (Isopoda, Valvifera, Chaetiliidae). Scientia Marina, 69 (S 2), 175 - 181." type="journal article" year="2005">
Held &amp; Wägele 
<number box="[395,454,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2005.0">2005</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Raupach" box="[466,755,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" refString="Raupach, M. J. &amp; Wagele, J. (2006) Distinguishing cryptic species in Antarctic Asellota (Crustacea: Isopoda) - a preliminary study of mitochondrial DNA in Acanthaspidia drygalskii. Antarctic Science, 18 (02), 191 - 198." type="journal article" year="2006">
Raupach &amp; Wägele 
<number box="[695,755,223,247]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), genetic data provide important independent information to test species hypotheses. The data of the 
<number box="[615,657,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="658.0">658</number>
bp CO 
<number box="[746,755,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
alignment from this study adds genetic support in favor of 
<bibRefCitation box="[151,381,295,319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" refString="Brokeland, W. (2010 a) Redescription of Haploniscus rostratus (Menzies, 1962) (Crustacea: Peracarida: Isopoda) with observations on the postmarsupial development, size ranges and distribution. Zootaxa, 2521, 1 - 25." type="journal article">
Brökeland´s (
<number box="[302,361,295,319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2010.0">2010</number>
a)
</bibRefCitation>
conclusion of gene flow across the Walvis Ridge. Our data resolve a single, well-supported 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">H. rostratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (posterior probability 0.95, ML Bootstrap 
<number box="[804,833,332,356]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="98.0">98</number>
) including both, the specimen from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1282,1364,332,356]" name="Angola" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Angola</collectingCountry>
Basin (
<collectionCode box="[158,230,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">DIVA</collectionCode>
<number box="[230,243,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2.0">2</number>
-HA 
<number box="[292,335,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="469.0">469</number>
, station 
<number box="[428,457,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="45.0">45</number>
) as well as those from the Cape Basin (
<number box="[899,928,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="16.0">16</number>
sequences from stations 
<number box="[1209,1237,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="40.0">40</number>
and 
<number box="[1291,1322,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="41.0">41</number>
). Interestingly, the single specimen available for analysis from the 
<collectingCountry box="[808,889,404,428]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Guinea</collectingCountry>
Basin (
<collectionCode box="[976,1048,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">DIVA</collectionCode>
<number box="[1049,1062,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2.0">2</number>
-HA 
<number box="[1111,1154,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="497.0">497</number>
, station 
<number box="[1249,1280,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="89.0">89</number>
), which is far more to the north, forms the sister group to the Cape and 
<collectingCountry box="[794,877,439,463]" name="Angola" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Angola</collectingCountry>
Basin group and is genetically distinct (about 
<number box="[1398,1412,439,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="7.0">7</number>
% uncorrected 
<emphasis box="[291,305,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">p</emphasis>
-distance; 
<figureCitation box="[422,487,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1746,1769]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,743,1715]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,730,1729]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. CO 1 Bayesian phylogenetic tree based on the 658 bp alignment. Branch support shows the ML / MP bootstrap values / posterior probabilities, respectively. (CB) = Cape Basin, (AB) = Angola Basin, (GB) = Guinea basin, (ARB) = ArgentinianBasin." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201728/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">
Fig. 
<number box="[474,487,476,500]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). This specimen was clearly identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[967,1102,477,500]" class="Malacostraca" family="Haploniscidae" genus="Haploniscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis box="[967,1102,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">H. rostratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Brökeland (pers. comm.), indicating possible barriers to gene flow among the southern basins and the northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1141,1222,511,535]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Guinea</collectingCountry>
Basin or even the presence of yet overlooked species. We conclude that although our dataset is rather small, it supports Brökeland’s (
<number box="[159,218,583,607]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="2010.0">2010</number>
a) hypothesis of recent or ongoing gene flow across the Walvis Ridge as specimens from the 
<collectingCountry box="[1281,1363,583,607]" name="Angola" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Angola</collectingCountry>
Basin and the Cape Basin share a single CO 
<number box="[579,588,620,644]" pageId="3" pageNumber="82" value="1.0">1</number>
haplotype. In addition, our data support the possible existence of cryptic or yet overlooked species occurring in the deep 
<collectingCountry box="[657,738,655,679]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="3" pageNumber="82">Guinea</collectingCountry>
Basin.
</paragraph>
